post_text: Ticket vouchers for indoor athletic events (Volleyball and Junior High Girls Basketball) will be in effect for the fall of 2020. Each volleyball and junior high girls basketball athlete and coach will receive (2) ticket vouchers for away contests, and (4) ticket vouchers for all home contests. The vouchers contain a health screening questionnaire that must be completed prior to entering the building. These vouchers must be presented to the ticket seller at the main entrance in order to purchase a ticket. Admission prices are $5.00 per person. Only those that have a voucher for the event listed will be allowed to enter the gymnasium. If you have any questions, please contact Mark Lane at the Wakefield-Marenisco School.

With the MHSAA postponing the fall football season to spring 2021, I want to say that I am very proud of the work that our Miners have put in during the summer offseason. We are extremely proud of the dedication, leadership, motivation and hard work that us coaches witnessed during this week of practice. You‚Äôve all worked hard and studied diligently to prepare yourselves to be put in the best possible position to be great this fall. I ask that you all stay motivated, dedicated and remain ALL IN for this upcoming spring season. We will do everything within our power to prepare you for this unique opportunity of a spring season. Stay positive, stay healthy, and Go Miners!
-Coach Heikkila

post_text:
Wakefield-Marenisco School Transportation Changes

In an effort to reduce school bus crowding, parents are asked to drive their children to school or have their children walk or ride their bikes to school if possible.

*Masks are required of anyone who rides the school bus. Masks must be worn over the mouth and nose for the entire ride.

*Students are asked to sanitize their hands when boarding the bus. Sanitizer will be provided.

*To reduce congestion, buses will drop off and pick up students in the north bus circle of the school. Parents will continue to pick up students at the usual spot in the south parking lot. Please do not block the west exit by parking in it.

post_text:
A new health self-screening tool will be required of all staff and visitors when we return to school. The health screening tool is available digitally through this link. QR codes will also be placed near the school entrance. If you need to visit the school and don't have access to the digital version, please report to the school office where you will be required to fill out a paper version of the tool.

Students will not be required to complete the screening tool. However, as part of the State of Michigan's return to school plan, parents are strongly encouraged to screen their children at home each morning before school. The screening takes only a few seconds.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we take all appropriate measures to ensure the health and safety of our students and staff.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1MINb4lMaQxWJdnYfkiABvy16-YQlg88lwSDEB37H5UQ/

post_text: Graduation will be held this Friday, July 10th at 6:00 p.m. At this point, the weather looks to be hot and dry. The ceremony will be held in the north school yard by Sunday Lake. The number of guests should be as limited as possible. Guests can park in the school parking lot and enter the school at door number 2, then walk directly to the exit opposite of door 2 to get to the school yard. A limited number of chairs will be set up in the grassy area by the north entrance. Chairs will be set up in groups of 2, and will be spaced 6 feet apart. Social distancing is expected of all who attend. This will not be a typical ceremony, but will be a nice farewell to the Wakefield-Marenisco Class of 2020!

post_text:
Wakefield-Marenisco Families

The WM Staff has had a lot of fun over the years planning surprising send-offs for our students on the last day of school. Even though this has not been a normal school year, we would still like to wish everyone farewell for the summer.
Buses carrying the staff will be traveling past students' houses (GSRP-Grade 11) on Thursday, June 4, which would have been our last day of school. The route will start at approximately 10:00 in Ironwood, making our way to Bessemer, Wakefield, Marenisco, and Bruces Crossing. The buses will not be stopping, but will slow near houses to give us time to say goodbye and wish everyone a good summer. We'll be watching for everyone in your yards, and can't wait to see your smiling faces.

post_text: Press Box Update: Construction on the football/track press box has begun. We just wanted to clarify that funds for this project were committed prior to the COVID19 outbreak. Although the future of fall sports is uncertain, the press box will move forward since we are bound by a building contract. The funds used for the building are part of building and grounds funds. The funds in the building and grounds fund can not be used for anything other than building and grounds projects. The building and grounds funds can not be reallocated in any other way for the school to use.

GRADUATION PARADE

The staff and school board of the Wakefield-Marenisco School will be honoring the Class of 2020 with a graduation parade! The parade will be held on Friday, May 22nd at 6:00 p.m. (The date and time originally scheduled for graduation.)

Students: Banners with each student‚Äôs picture on them will be mounted on the street lights along M-28 by Sunday Lake. The banners will start at the visitor center and end near the football field. Please park your car either in the bus loop facing Sunday Lake, or somewhere on the side of M-28 prior to 6:00 p.m. Then please stand by the pole that has your banner on it. Feel free to bring some family members with you, but be sure to practice social distancing. The parade of staff members and community members will start at 6:00 near the State Police Post and follow along M-28 then loop over to Putnam Blvd.

Community members are welcome to watch the parade, but please be sure to practice social distancing.

post_text:
As we enter Teacher Appreciation Week, I would like to take a few moments to recognize and thank not only our teachers, but all staff members of the Wakefield-Marenisco School District. We have seen more than ever over the past couple of months how we work together as one to meet the needs of our students. Whether driving the school bus, teaching classes, working as a classroom aide, performing office work, or working in the lunchroom, the employees of the Wakefield-Marenisco School District share a common vision. The vision is to do whatever is necessary to provide the best education and educational setting possible for our students. Our staff members touch the lives of our students in so many ways, and for that I am thankful. Even though we are not together in a traditional manner this year, please know that I apprecite you and everything you do for our students day in and day out. Thank you!

Jason Gustafson, Superintendent

Stay home and stay safe!
-Mr. Switzer

Pickup time will be from 1:00-2:00 on Monday. Students will not be allowed into the school to get the eggs, but can pick them up outside the main entrance to the school. post_text: Work Packet Clarification: Most teachers sent home work packets or made assignments in Google Classroom for their students. This work is for enrichment only. post_text: Nothing gets 7/8 Art Students engaged like taking things apart and putting them back together as something else. We have been working on assemblage sculptures with a steampunk theme. Students in all classes take apart old appliances and computers throughout the year to create our stockpile of materials. The sculptures/machines need to have a job. They are based in the future and the past.
